figgy.title: Do not allow items within a collection to bulk complete without files attached

comments.body:
The most recent instance was the objects linked to AC111 in Pulfalight. There was a collection of objects with 2 objects with files, and several hundred without any files attached. All of the items were completed, and the items with no files attached resulted in blank viewers appearing in Pulfalight.

I don't know who bulk-completed the items, but Annalise confirmed one of the items with files attached was as it should be, and Chloe confirmed that the objects without files attached were from an abandoned attempt to attach groups of photos at the component level.

a couple ideas:
- Change the appearance of the form more dramatically when a value is selected for update (maybe highlight the whole field with a colored outline or something)
- Beef up the alert
  - make it say each field change rather than just the number of items
  - Make it a styled modal rather than a browser alert
  - require the user to type something rather than just click
  - have an alert for each field they want to change, maybe show the previous values?

This is just a brainstorm. But bulk edits are very powerful and the next time an edit is accidentally applied it may not be so easy to fix.

@hackartisan , I really like the idea of making the alert a styled modal (the red button for delete scanned resource gives many people a big pause before execution). "Are you sure you want to bulk edit 581 resources?" is pretty direct, but I do see your point about specifying what is being edited.

orangelight.title: Feedback form confirmation message should probably be reworded

comments.body:
Noting that there is a honeypot on this form.  Steps to exercise the honeypot:

1. Open mailcatcher using the instructions in the README
2. Go to https://catalog-staging.princeton.edu/feedback
3. Fill out the form and submit
4. Note that an outgoing email to libanswers appears in the mailcatcher.
5. Go back to https://catalog-staging.princeton.edu/feedback
6. Apply this CSS rule in your browser to make the honeypot field appear:
```
.blacklight-feedback-hidden {
  display: block;
}
```
7. Fill out the whole form, including the honeypot field, and submit
8. Note that the form gives you a success message, but no email appears in the mailcatcher.

So we need to focus on the spam is not fooled by the honeypot.
